	<title>Exercises: Completeness of the Real Number System</title>
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the sets below determine if it is bounded above or below. If so suggest an upper, respectively a lower bound.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The set <latex>S:=\CCIntrvl{-10}{10}</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>This set is bounded above by <latex>10</latex> or any <latex>u\in \RNr</latex> with <latex>u\geq 10</latex>. It is bounded below by <latex>-10</latex> or any <latex>l\in \RNr</latex> with <latex>l\leq -10</latex>.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The set <latex magnify="yes">T:=\Set{ \tfrac{x}{x+3}\in \RNr \st x\geq 0 }</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para>This set is bounded below by any <latex>l\in \RNr</latex> with <latex>l\leq 0</latex>. It is bounded above by any <latex>u\in \RNr</latex> with <latex>u\geq 1</latex>.</para>
				</answer>
				<solution.hint>
					<para>The elements of <latex>T</latex> are ratios of the form <latex magnify="yes">\tfrac{x}{x+3}</latex> with <latex>x\geq 0</latex>. So compare the size of numerator <latex>x</latex> to the size of the denominator <latex>x+3</latex>.</para>
				</solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The set <latex>\NNr</latex> of natural numbers.</para>
			</problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>The set <latex>\ZNr</latex> of integers</para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>The set <latex>\QNr</latex> of rational numbers</para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>The set <latex>U:=\Set{ t\in \RNr \st t^2\leq 4}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>The set <latex>V:=\Set{ s\in \RNr \st s^3\leq 8}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>The set <latex>A:=\Set{ x\in \RNr \st \sin x \geq 0}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>The set <latex>B:=\Set{ y\in \RNr \st \cos y \geq 2}</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>In each of the problems below use the completeness axiom to show that there is exactly one number with the stated property. Then show that this number is not rational.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem><para>a number <latex>x</latex> with <latex>x^2=3</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>a number <latex>s</latex> with <latex>s^2=5</latex></para></problem>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>If <latex>t\in\NNr</latex> is a prime number, a number <latex>x</latex> with <latex>x^2=t</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
	</exercise>
